Note:
x86 (IA-32) Register Allocator - Architecture-Specific Constraint Resolution

Resolves x86 32-bit register allocation constraints after middle-end graph coloring.
x86 32-bit has only 8 general-purpose registers (EAX-EDI), no REX-extended registers.
All constraints are identical to x86_64 (two-address form, IDIV, shift-CL) but
operate within the restricted 8-register GPR file.

Key differences from x86_64:
- Only 8 GPRs (0-7): EAX, EBX, ECX, EDX, ESI, EDI, EBP, ESP
- No R8-R15 registers (no REX prefix available)
- Higher register pressure leads to more frequent spills
- 32-bit operand sizes instead of 64-bit
- CDQ instead of CQO for sign extension before IDIV

Dependencies:
- Imports LIR types for function, block, and instruction structures
- Imports LIRNodes for operand creation and instruction construction
- Imports memory/layout.runa for OWNED HEAP allocation (Tier 3)
- Imports list.runa for collection manipulation
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir.runa" as LIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir_nodes.runa" as LIRNodes
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: x86 32-bit Register Constants
Note: Only 8 GPRs available - no REX-extended registers
Note: ============================================================================

Constant REG_EAX as Integer is 0
Constant REG_EBX as Integer is 1
Constant REG_ECX as Integer is 2
Constant REG_EDX as Integer is 3
Constant REG_ESI as Integer is 4
Constant REG_EDI as Integer is 5
Constant REG_EBP as Integer is 6
Constant REG_ESP as Integer is 7

Note: Total allocatable GPRs (EBP and ESP are reserved)
Constant X86_GPR_COUNT as Integer is 8
Constant X86_ALLOCATABLE_COUNT as Integer is 6

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LIR Opcode Constants (mirrored from LIR for local convenience)
Note: ============================================================================

Constant OP_MOV as Integer is 30001
Constant OP_ADD as Integer is 30100
Constant OP_SUB as Integer is 30101
Constant OP_IMUL as Integer is 30102
Constant OP_IDIV as Integer is 30103
Constant OP_MUL as Integer is 30104
Constant OP_DIV as Integer is 30105
Constant OP_NEG as Integer is 30106
Constant OP_ADC as Integer is 30109
Constant OP_SBB as Integer is 30110
Constant OP_AND as Integer is 30200
Constant OP_OR as Integer is 30201
Constant OP_XOR as Integer is 30202
Constant OP_NOT as Integer is 30203
Constant OP_SHL as Integer is 30300
Constant OP_SHR as Integer is 30301
Constant OP_SAR as Integer is 30302
Constant OP_ROL as Integer is 30303
Constant OP_ROR as Integer is 30304

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Constraint Type Constants
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
x86 32-bit shares the same instruction encoding constraints as x86_64:
- Two-address form: dest overwrites first source operand (ADD, SUB, AND, OR, XOR, etc.)
- IDIV/DIV: implicit EAX:EDX dividend pair (32-bit instead of 64-bit)
- Shift/rotate with variable count: shift count must reside in CL (low byte of ECX)
- Higher register pressure due to only 6 allocatable registers (EAX, EBX, ECX, EDX, ESI, EDI)
@End Reasoning

Constant CONSTRAINT_TWO_ADDRESS as Integer is 1
Constant CONSTRAINT_FIXED_REG as Integer is 2
Constant CONSTRAINT_CLOBBER as Integer is 3
Constant CONSTRAINT_SHIFT_CL as Integer is 4
Constant CONSTRAINT_DIV_EAX_EDX as Integer is 5

Note: ============================================================================
Note: X86AllocConstraint Type Definition
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Each constraint record describes a single x86-specific register constraint.
Identical layout to x86_64 constraints but operating on 32-bit register file.

Fields:
- instruction_index: position of the constrained instruction within its block
- constraint_type: one of the CONSTRAINT_* constants
- required_register: physical register an operand must reside in
- operand_index: which operand is constrained (0=result, 1=op1, 2=op2, 3=op3)
- block_index: index of the basic block containing the constrained instruction
@End Reasoning

Type called "X86AllocConstraint":
    instruction_index as Integer
    constraint_type as Integer
    required_register as Integer
    operand_index as Integer
    block_index as Integer
End Type

Note: Size: 5 fields * 8 bytes = 40 bytes per X86AllocConstraint

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Register Information Queries
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "is_allocatable_register" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns 1 if the register is available for general allocation
    Note: EBP (6) and ESP (7) are reserved for frame and stack pointer
    If reg_id is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg_id is greater than 7:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg_id is 6:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg_id is 7:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "is_callee_saved" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: cdecl calling convention: EBX, ESI, EDI, EBP are callee-saved
    If reg_id is 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If reg_id is 4:
        Return 1
    End If
    If reg_id is 5:
        Return 1
    End If
    If reg_id is 6:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "is_caller_saved" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: cdecl calling convention: EAX, ECX, EDX are caller-saved (scratch)
    If reg_id is 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    If reg_id is 2:
        Return 1
    End If
    If reg_id is 3:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "get_allocatable_registers" returns Integer:
    Note: Returns a List of allocatable register IDs for x86 32-bit
    Note: Order is allocation preference: scratch registers first, then callee-saved
    Let regs be List.list_create(8)
    If regs is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Note: Scratch registers preferred (no save/restore cost)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_EAX)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_ECX)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_EDX)
    Note: Callee-saved registers (require save/restore in prologue/epilogue)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_EBX)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_ESI)
    List.list_append(regs, REG_EDI)
    Return regs
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Virtual-to-Physical Register Mapping
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Maps LIR virtual register IDs to x86 32-bit physical registers.
With only 6 allocatable registers, spilling is more frequent.
Virtual register IDs 0-7 map directly to physical registers.
Virtual register IDs > or equal to 8 must be assigned through graph coloring
or spilled to stack memory.

The allocation priority favors scratch registers (EAX, ECX, EDX) over
callee-saved registers (EBX, ESI, EDI) to minimize prologue/epilogue overhead.
@End Reasoning

Process called "map_virtual_to_physical" that takes virtual_reg as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Direct mapping for virtual registers 0-5 to allocatable physical registers
    Note: Returns -1 if the virtual register must be spilled
    If virtual_reg is 0:
        Return REG_EAX
    End If
    If virtual_reg is 1:
        Return REG_ECX
    End If
    If virtual_reg is 2:
        Return REG_EDX
    End If
    If virtual_reg is 3:
        Return REG_EBX
    End If
    If virtual_reg is 4:
        Return REG_ESI
    End If
    If virtual_reg is 5:
        Return REG_EDI
    End If
    Note: Virtual register exceeds physical register count; needs spill
    Return 0 minus 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Constraint Collection
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Scans every instruction in every basic block of the given LIR function and emits
constraint descriptors for instructions requiring x86-specific register fixups.

Identical constraint categories as x86_64:
- Two-address: ADD, SUB, AND, OR, XOR, ADC, SBB, IMUL
- Division: IDIV, DIV (uses EAX:EDX pair, 32-bit)
- Shift/rotate: SHL, SHR, SAR, ROL, ROR with register count (requires CL)

Returns a List of pointers to X86AllocConstraint structures.
@End Reasoning

Process called "collect_x86_constraints" that takes lir_function as Integer returns Integer:
    If lir_function is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let constraints be List.list_create(32)
    If constraints is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Retrieve basic blocks from the LIR function
    Let blocks be __load(lir_function, 32)
    Let block_count be __load(lir_function, 40)

    If blocks is 0:
        Return constraints
    End If
    If block_count is 0:
        Return constraints
    End If

    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be List.list_get(blocks, b)
        If block is not 0:
            Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
            Let inst_count be __load(block, 24)

            If instructions is not 0:
                Let i be 0
                While i is less than inst_count:
                    Let instruction be List.list_get(instructions, i)
                    If instruction is not 0:
                        Let opcode be __load(instruction, 0)

                        Note: ---- Two-address form constraints ----
                        Note: ADD, SUB, AND, OR, XOR, ADC, SBB
                        If opcode is OP_ADD:
                            Let c be create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_TWO_ADDRESS, 0 minus 1, 0, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c)
                        End If
                        If opcode is OP_SUB:
                            Let c be create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_TWO_ADDRESS, 0 minus 1, 0, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c)
                        End If
                        If opcode is OP_AND:
                            Let c be create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_TWO_ADDRESS, 0 minus 1, 0, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c)
                        End If
                        If opcode is OP_OR:
                            Let c be create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_TWO_ADDRESS, 0 minus 1, 0, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c)
                        End If
                        If opcode is OP_XOR:
                            Let c be create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_TWO_ADDRESS, 0 minus 1, 0, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c)
                        End If
                        If opcode is OP_ADC:
                            Let c be create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_TWO_ADDRESS, 0 minus 1, 0, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c)
                        End If
                        If opcode is OP_SBB:
                            Let c be create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_TWO_ADDRESS, 0 minus 1, 0, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c)
                        End If

                        Note: IMUL two-operand form is also two-address
                        If opcode is OP_IMUL:
                            Let c be create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_TWO_ADDRESS, 0 minus 1, 0, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c)
                        End If

                        Note: ---- Division constraints ----
                        If opcode is OP_IDIV:
                            Let c be create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_DIV_EAX_EDX, REG_EAX, 1, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c)
                        End If
                        If opcode is OP_DIV:
                            Let c be create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_DIV_EAX_EDX, REG_EAX, 1, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c)
                        End If

                        Note: ---- Shift/rotate CL constraints ----
                        If opcode is OP_SHL:
                            Let c be create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_TWO_ADDRESS, 0 minus 1, 0, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c)
                            check_shift_cl_constraint(instruction, i, b, constraints)
                        End If
                        If opcode is OP_SHR:
                            Let c be create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_TWO_ADDRESS, 0 minus 1, 0, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c)
                            check_shift_cl_constraint(instruction, i, b, constraints)
                        End If
                        If opcode is OP_SAR:
                            Let c be create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_TWO_ADDRESS, 0 minus 1, 0, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c)
                            check_shift_cl_constraint(instruction, i, b, constraints)
                        End If
                        If opcode is OP_ROL:
                            Let c be create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_TWO_ADDRESS, 0 minus 1, 0, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c)
                            check_shift_cl_constraint(instruction, i, b, constraints)
                        End If
                        If opcode is OP_ROR:
                            Let c be create_constraint(i, CONSTRAINT_TWO_ADDRESS, 0 minus 1, 0, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, c)
                            check_shift_cl_constraint(instruction, i, b, constraints)
                        End If
                    End If

                    Set i to i plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return constraints
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Internal Helpers
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "create_constraint" that takes inst_idx as Integer, ctype as Integer, req_reg as Integer, op_idx as Integer, blk_idx as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Allocates and initializes a constraint record
    Let c be Layout.allocate(40)
    If c is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    __store(c, 0, inst_idx)
    __store(c, 8, ctype)
    __store(c, 16, req_reg)
    __store(c, 24, op_idx)
    __store(c, 32, blk_idx)
    Return c
End Process

Process called "check_shift_cl_constraint" that takes instruction as Integer, inst_idx as Integer, blk_idx as Integer, constraints as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: If operand2 (shift count) is a register operand, emit CONSTRAINT_SHIFT_CL
    Let operand2_ptr be __load(instruction, 24)
    If operand2_ptr is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let op2_type be __load(operand2_ptr, 0)
    If op2_type is 1:
        Note: Register operand - shift count must be in CL
        Let c be create_constraint(inst_idx, CONSTRAINT_SHIFT_CL, REG_ECX, 2, blk_idx)
        List.list_append(constraints, c)
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Register Copy Insertion
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Creates a new LIR MOV instruction and inserts it into the given basic block's
instruction list at the specified position (before the instruction at before_index).

Identical to x86_64 register copy insertion but with 4-byte operand size default
instead of 8-byte. Both operands are register operands.

After insertion, instruction indices in the block are shifted.
Returns 1 on success, 0 on failure.
@End Reasoning

Process called "insert_register_copy" that takes block as Integer, before_index as Integer, dest_reg as Integer, src_reg as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    If block is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Do not insert a copy if source and destination are the same register
    If dest_reg is src_reg:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Create the MOV instruction
    Let mov_instruction be LIRNodes.create_lir_instruction(OP_MOV)
    If mov_instruction is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create register operands for destination and source
    Let dest_operand be LIRNodes.create_register_operand(dest_reg, size)
    If dest_operand is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let src_operand be LIRNodes.create_register_operand(src_reg, size)
    If src_operand is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Wire up the MOV instruction: result = dest, operand1 = src
    __store(mov_instruction, 8, dest_operand)
    __store(mov_instruction, 16, src_operand)
    __store(mov_instruction, 48, block)

    Note: Insert into the block's instruction list at before_index
    Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
    If instructions is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    List.list_insert_at(instructions, before_index, mov_instruction)

    Note: Update instruction count in the block
    Let inst_count be __load(block, 24)
    __store(block, 24, inst_count plus 1)

    Note: Update instruction_index for all instructions from before_index onward
    Let new_count be inst_count plus 1
    Let idx be before_index
    While idx is less than new_count:
        Let inst be List.list_get(instructions, idx)
        If inst is not 0:
            __store(inst, 64, idx)
        End If
        Set idx to idx plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Two-Address Form Resolution
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Resolves two-address form constraint for a single instruction on x86.
If dest register differs from src1 register, inserts MOV src1 -> dest
before the instruction and rewrites operand1 to use dest register.

Identical logic to x86_64 but constrained to registers 0-7.
@End Reasoning

Process called "handle_two_address_form" that takes lir_function as Integer, instruction as Integer, block as Integer, inst_index as Integer returns Integer:
    If instruction is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If block is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Read result operand pointer (offset 8) and operand1 pointer (offset 16)
    Let result_ptr be __load(instruction, 8)
    Let operand1_ptr be __load(instruction, 16)

    If result_ptr is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If operand1_ptr is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Both must be register operands
    Let result_type be __load(result_ptr, 0)
    Let op1_type be __load(operand1_ptr, 0)
    If result_type is not 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If op1_type is not 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let dest_reg be __load(result_ptr, 8)
    Let src1_reg be __load(operand1_ptr, 8)
    Let operand_size be __load(result_ptr, 56)

    Note: Default to 4 bytes if size is unset (32-bit architecture)
    If operand_size is 0:
        Set operand_size to 4
    End If

    Note: If dest and src1 are the same register, constraint is satisfied
    If dest_reg is src1_reg:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Insert MOV src1 -> dest before this instruction
    Let success be insert_register_copy(block, inst_index, dest_reg, src1_reg, operand_size)
    If success is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Rewrite operand1 to use dest_reg (now contains src1 value)
    __store(operand1_ptr, 8, dest_reg)

    Note: One instruction was inserted
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Division Constraint Resolution
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Resolves IDIV/DIV constraints on x86 32-bit.

x86 32-bit integer division:
  IDIV r/m32 => signed divide EDX:EAX by r/m32
                quotient  -> EAX
                remainder -> EDX

  DIV  r/m32 => unsigned divide EDX:EAX by r/m32
                quotient  -> EAX
                remainder -> EDX

For IDIV (signed), inserts before the IDIV:
  MOV EAX, <dividend>       (move dividend to EAX)
  CDQ                       (sign-extend EAX into EDX:EAX)

For DIV (unsigned), inserts before the DIV:
  MOV EAX, <dividend>       (move dividend to EAX)
  XOR EDX, EDX              (zero EDX for unsigned division)

After division, if result register is not EAX:
  MOV <dest>, EAX           (copy quotient to destination)
@End Reasoning

Process called "handle_division_constraint" that takes lir_function as Integer, instruction as Integer, block as Integer, inst_index as Integer returns Integer:
    If instruction is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If block is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let opcode be __load(instruction, 0)
    Let result_ptr be __load(instruction, 8)
    Let operand1_ptr be __load(instruction, 16)

    If operand1_ptr is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let inserted_count be 0

    Note: Get the dividend register (operand1)
    Let op1_type be __load(operand1_ptr, 0)
    Let dividend_reg be 0
    If op1_type is 1:
        Set dividend_reg to __load(operand1_ptr, 8)
    End If

    Note: Step 1: Move dividend into EAX if not already there
    If dividend_reg is not REG_EAX:
        Let success be insert_register_copy(block, inst_index plus inserted_count, REG_EAX, dividend_reg, 4)
        If success is 1:
            Set inserted_count to inserted_count plus 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: Step 2: Set up EDX (sign-extend or zero)
    If opcode is OP_IDIV:
        Note: For signed division, sign-extend EAX into EDX:EAX
        Note: This is equivalent to CDQ: EDX = (EAX >> 31) ? 0xFFFFFFFF : 0x00000000
        Note: Emit: MOV EDX, EAX then SAR EDX, 31
        Let mov_inst be LIRNodes.create_lir_instruction(OP_MOV)
        If mov_inst is not 0:
            Let dest_op be LIRNodes.create_register_operand(REG_EDX, 4)
            Let src_op be LIRNodes.create_register_operand(REG_EAX, 4)
            __store(mov_inst, 8, dest_op)
            __store(mov_inst, 16, src_op)
            __store(mov_inst, 48, block)
            Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
            List.list_insert_at(instructions, inst_index plus inserted_count, mov_inst)
            Let ic be __load(block, 24)
            __store(block, 24, ic plus 1)
            Set inserted_count to inserted_count plus 1
        End If

        Note: SAR EDX, 31 for sign extension
        Let sar_inst be LIRNodes.create_lir_instruction(OP_SAR)
        If sar_inst is not 0:
            Let sar_dest be LIRNodes.create_register_operand(REG_EDX, 4)
            Let sar_src be LIRNodes.create_register_operand(REG_EDX, 4)
            Let sar_imm be LIRNodes.create_immediate_operand(31, 4)
            __store(sar_inst, 8, sar_dest)
            __store(sar_inst, 16, sar_src)
            __store(sar_inst, 24, sar_imm)
            __store(sar_inst, 48, block)
            Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
            List.list_insert_at(instructions, inst_index plus inserted_count, sar_inst)
            Let ic be __load(block, 24)
            __store(block, 24, ic plus 1)
            Set inserted_count to inserted_count plus 1
        End If
    End If

    If opcode is OP_DIV:
        Note: For unsigned division, zero EDX via XOR EDX, EDX
        Let xor_inst be LIRNodes.create_lir_instruction(OP_XOR)
        If xor_inst is not 0:
            Let xor_dest be LIRNodes.create_register_operand(REG_EDX, 4)
            Let xor_src be LIRNodes.create_register_operand(REG_EDX, 4)
            __store(xor_inst, 8, xor_dest)
            __store(xor_inst, 16, xor_src)
            __store(xor_inst, 24, xor_src)
            __store(xor_inst, 48, block)
            Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
            List.list_insert_at(instructions, inst_index plus inserted_count, xor_inst)
            Let ic be __load(block, 24)
            __store(block, 24, ic plus 1)
            Set inserted_count to inserted_count plus 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: Step 3: If the result register is not EAX, copy quotient from EAX to dest
    If result_ptr is not 0:
        Let result_type be __load(result_ptr, 0)
        If result_type is 1:
            Let dest_reg be __load(result_ptr, 8)
            If dest_reg is not REG_EAX:
                Note: Insert MOV after the IDIV/DIV instruction
                Let after_idx be inst_index plus inserted_count plus 1
                Let success be insert_register_copy(block, after_idx, dest_reg, REG_EAX, 4)
                If success is 1:
                    Set inserted_count to inserted_count plus 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Reindex all instructions from the insertion point
    Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
    Let total_count be __load(block, 24)
    Let idx be inst_index
    While idx is less than total_count:
        Let inst be List.list_get(instructions, idx)
        If inst is not 0:
            __store(inst, 64, idx)
        End If
        Set idx to idx plus 1
    End While

    Return inserted_count
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Shift CL Constraint Resolution
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Resolves the shift-CL constraint: variable-count shifts and rotates on x86
require the shift count in the CL register (low byte of ECX).

If the count operand is in a different register, inserts MOV to ECX before
the instruction and rewrites operand2 to reference ECX.
@End Reasoning

Process called "handle_shift_cl_constraint" that takes lir_function as Integer, instruction as Integer, block as Integer, inst_index as Integer returns Integer:
    If instruction is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If block is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let operand2_ptr be __load(instruction, 24)
    If operand2_ptr is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let op2_type be __load(operand2_ptr, 0)
    Note: Only register operands need CL fixup; immediates are encoded directly
    If op2_type is not 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count_reg be __load(operand2_ptr, 8)
    Note: If already in ECX, no fixup needed
    If count_reg is REG_ECX:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Insert MOV count_reg -> ECX before the instruction
    Let success be insert_register_copy(block, inst_index, REG_ECX, count_reg, 4)
    If success is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Rewrite operand2 to reference ECX
    __store(operand2_ptr, 8, REG_ECX)

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Complete Constraint Resolution Pass
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Main entry point for x86 32-bit register constraint resolution.
Collects all constraints, then resolves them in reverse order (to avoid
index invalidation when inserting instructions).

Processing order:
1. Collect all constraints for the function
2. Sort by block_index then instruction_index (descending)
3. Process each constraint:
   - CONSTRAINT_TWO_ADDRESS -> handle_two_address_form
   - CONSTRAINT_DIV_EAX_EDX -> handle_division_constraint
   - CONSTRAINT_SHIFT_CL -> handle_shift_cl_constraint
4. Run move coalescing to remove redundant MOV r, r instructions
@End Reasoning

Process called "resolve_x86_constraints" that takes lir_function as Integer returns Integer:
    If lir_function is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let constraints be collect_x86_constraints(lir_function)
    If constraints is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let constraint_count be List.list_length(constraints)
    If constraint_count is 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Process constraints in reverse order to preserve instruction indices
    Let ci be constraint_count minus 1
    While ci is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let constraint be List.list_get(constraints, ci)
        If constraint is not 0:
            Let inst_idx be __load(constraint, 0)
            Let ctype be __load(constraint, 8)
            Let blk_idx be __load(constraint, 32)

            Note: Get the block and instruction
            Let blocks be __load(lir_function, 32)
            Let block be List.list_get(blocks, blk_idx)
            If block is not 0:
                Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
                Let instruction be List.list_get(instructions, inst_idx)
                If instruction is not 0:
                    If ctype is CONSTRAINT_TWO_ADDRESS:
                        handle_two_address_form(lir_function, instruction, block, inst_idx)
                    End If
                    If ctype is CONSTRAINT_DIV_EAX_EDX:
                        handle_division_constraint(lir_function, instruction, block, inst_idx)
                    End If
                    If ctype is CONSTRAINT_SHIFT_CL:
                        handle_shift_cl_constraint(lir_function, instruction, block, inst_idx)
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set ci to ci minus 1
    End While

    Note: Coalesce redundant moves
    coalesce_moves(lir_function)

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Move Coalescing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
After constraint resolution, redundant MOV instructions may exist where
source and destination are the same register (MOV EAX, EAX). This pass
scans all blocks and removes such no-op moves.
@End Reasoning

Process called "coalesce_moves" that takes lir_function as Integer returns Integer:
    If lir_function is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let blocks be __load(lir_function, 32)
    Let block_count be __load(lir_function, 40)
    If blocks is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let removed_count be 0
    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be List.list_get(blocks, b)
        If block is not 0:
            Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
            Let inst_count be __load(block, 24)
            If instructions is not 0:
                Let i be inst_count minus 1
                While i is greater than or equal to 0:
                    Let inst be List.list_get(instructions, i)
                    If inst is not 0:
                        Let opcode be __load(inst, 0)
                        If opcode is OP_MOV:
                            Let result_ptr be __load(inst, 8)
                            Let operand1_ptr be __load(inst, 16)
                            If result_ptr is not 0:
                                If operand1_ptr is not 0:
                                    Let r_type be __load(result_ptr, 0)
                                    Let o_type be __load(operand1_ptr, 0)
                                    If r_type is 1:
                                        If o_type is 1:
                                            Let r_reg be __load(result_ptr, 8)
                                            Let o_reg be __load(operand1_ptr, 8)
                                            If r_reg is o_reg:
                                                Note: Remove this redundant MOV
                                                List.list_remove_at(instructions, i)
                                                Let new_count be __load(block, 24)
                                                __store(block, 24, new_count minus 1)
                                                Set removed_count to removed_count plus 1
                                            End If
                                        End If
                                    End If
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                    Set i to i minus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If
        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return removed_count
End Process
